Renaming the Columns¶

As mentioned in data description, it contains the following 6 fields. Looking at the top part of the dataset we can depioct each column. We can describe them briefly as:¶

0 - target: the polarity of the tweet (0 = negative, 2 = neutral, 4 = positive)¶

1 - ids: The id of the tweet ( 2087)¶

2 - date of the tweet (Sat May 16 23:58:44 UTC 2009)¶

3 - flag: The query, if there is no query, then this value is NO_QUERY, in each row contains 'NO_QUERY'¶

4 - the user that tweeted¶

5 - the text of the tweet¶

In [7]:
df = df.rename(columns={0: 'target', 1: 'ids', 2: 'date', 3: 'flag', 4: 'username', 5: 'text'})

STOPWORDS = set(stopwords.words('english'))
def cleaning_stopwords(text):
    return " ".join([word for word in str(text).split() if word not in STOPWORDS])
df['text'] = df['text'].apply(lambda text: cleaning_stopwords(text))

Dealing with usernames and urls¶

In [12]:
def cleaning_all(text):
    text= re.sub('@\S+|https?:\S+|http?:\S|[^A-Za-z0-9]+', ' ', text)
    text = text.lower()
    text = text.split()
    return text
In [13]:
df['text']= df['text'].apply(lambda x: cleaning_all(x))

Stemming¶

Using the base of english stopwords and stemming algorithm from nltk library

In [14]:
stm = nltk.PorterStemmer()
def stemmer(t):
    text = [stm.stem(word) for word in t]
    return t
In [14]:
df['text']= df['text'].apply(lambda x: stemmer(x))

Lemmatizer¶

In [40]:
lem = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer()
def lemmatizer(t):
    text = [lem.lemmatize(word) for word in t]
    return t
In [41]:

Task 7: Model Evaluation¶

In [11]:
def evaluate(model, X_test,  Y_test):
    Y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    print("Accuracy: ", accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred))
    print(classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred))
    print('Confusion Matrix:',ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(Y_test,Y_pred))
